Hello
 _JxW[_qp]

is the quadrature weights and the Jacobian for the transformation from the real element to the reference element
_coord[_qp]

is a factor for the integration in RZ/ RSpherical coordinates. In RZ the size of the infinitesimal integration quantity is 2pi r dr for example, so _coord is 2 pi r. (in xyz, domega = dxdyxdz so _coord = 1)
(0, 0) etc

are simply indices into the diagonal of the tensor.
Guillaume

node.bodyText:
Hello
The default is combining and solving both equations together.
If you assign the variables to different systems, you can now solve system separately. This is a current, ongoing, development. We have a separate solve between two systems in an Executioner test object that's it.
Your understanding is correct. Different systems are solved separately.
However what you did with auxiliary variables provided some degree of separation between the solves, but not to the extent of "different matrices" or "solved separately". There was still some coupling every time the auxkernel was run and it updated the variable.
Guillaume

I understand that there is still some coupling between different problems even after using auxvariables. However, my curiosity lies in whether it is feasible to utilize auxvariables to allocate different variables to distinct systems. The idea is to update auxvariables by exchanging information between different systems only after separately completing one iteration for all systems (not multiapp). Additionally, how can one go about assigning different variables to different systems?
You can look at https://github.com/idaholab/moose/tree/next/test/tests/misc/multiple-nl-systems

node.title: float problem
node.bodyText:
Dear MOOSE users,
Hope you are doing great! I tried to determine a material property. But the following error appears:
 "cannot convert field 'Materials/consts_expected/prop_values' value 'Kn*An*(exp(-Eact/(Kb*T)))*(exp(-Qgb/(Kb*T)))' to float"

The input file structure looks like that:
[Materials]
  [./consts_expected]
    type = GenericConstantMaterial
    prop_names =  'Kn      An     Eact     Qgb    Kb    T             N'
    prop_values = '1.11e8    10e4    4.8   1   8.6173303e-5    800   Kn*An*(exp(-Eact/(Kb*T)))*(exp(-Qgb/(Kb*T)))'
    outputs = exodus
  [../]

Any suggestion what is wrong? Any solution?
I would appreciate if you can manage time  to reply.
Thanks,
Zahid

hello
you need to parse the quantity down to a real before it gets fed into the material. You can get the parser to do that with:
Kn = 1.11e8
An = 10e4
Eact = 4.8
Qgb = 1
T =  8.6173303e-5
N = 800

[Materials]
  [./consts_expected]
    type = GenericConstantMaterial
    prop_names =  'Kn      An     Eact     Qgb    Kb    T             N'
    prop_values = '${Kn}    ${An}    ${Eact}   ${Qgb}  ${T}    ${N}  ${fparse Kn*An*(exp(-Eact/(Kb*T)))*(exp(-Qgb/(Kb*T)))}'
    outputs = exodus
  [../]

what I m doing here is that i m defining the quantities as input file variables, then using the parser to convert the whole expression into a Real number.
The ${N} are doing a substitution, a simple one with no other operation.
The ${fparse is doing a parsed calculation and a substitution
@GiudGiud Thanks. I appreciate.

The rule for MOOSE to store the information along the interface is within the elements which are connected to the interface, on the side of smaller subdomain IDs. Since I need to extract the information and do post-processing, I wonder what is the best way to extract the values from exodus file.
For example, in one of my simulation results using TRIA3, the tangent jump is stored in the TRIA elements:

How should I extract the values for this interface, I didn't find any group information provided by MOOSE or in paraview, what I currently do is to use netCDF4 to extract element values (but I would need to get the element ID myself) which is tricky sometime.
Any suggestion would be appreciated, thanks!
If you just select the interface boundary, (uncheck the blocks), you should be able to visualize the values at interface only. I guess it should work.
